document FindingCatalog: "Finding Catalog"
    "Use only these core Doctrine codes."
    "Choose the smallest correct code by recognition test, not by keyword match."
    "Use this file to calibrate what strong findings look like."

    markdown:
        text: """| Code | Title | Recognition test | Default recommendation |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| `AL100` | Oversized Always-On Context | The role home carries too much always-on text, or new local bulk does not buy clearer loading, stronger reuse, or exact truth. | Move deep reference material into a shared skill, module, or docs index. |
| `AL110` | Pasted Reference Instead Of Pointer | Long reference text is pasted where a shared pointer should exist. | Replace the pasted block with a pointer to one shared source. |
| `AL120` | Deep Procedure In The Role Home | A reusable method is taught inline instead of through a shared skill. A per-case decision taxonomy (if field X is populated, install rule Y; if Z appears, install rule W) is the canonical shape. | Move the reusable method into a skill. |
| `AL130` | Dead Inherited Section | Inherited text is present but not used. | Drop the inherit or move the pointer to the step that needs it. |
| `AL140` | Planning-Doc Scaffolding In Agent Body | The role body cites planning docs by path or rule ID, or carries authoring rationale. | Strip the citation and rule IDs; keep only the behavior. |
| `AL150` | Role Body Carries Markdown Section Tree | The `role:` value is a multiline string holding markdown headings (`##` / `###`) or a numbered section list, instead of typed workflow slots on the agent. The string's internal sections are invisible to the compiler. | Keep `role:` to a one-sentence headline. Move each internal heading into a typed agent slot (`your_job`, `workflow_core`, or any authored slot key) pointed at a `workflow` with titled children. |
| `AL200` | Duplicate Rule Across Agents | The same rule or step list appears in several agents. A fixed vocabulary written as a pipe list (for example `A \\| B \\| C`) and repeated on several roles or on the critic gate is a canonical shape. | Lift the repeated rule into one shared skill or module. For a pipe-list vocabulary, declare an `enum` and type the field with it. |
| `AL210` | Repeated Method Should Become A Skill | Several agents carry the same decision method without a shared skill owner. | Extract the shared method into a skill. |
| `AL220` | Repeated Background Block Across Agents | Several agent homes carry the same background or glossary block. | Move the shared background into one importable module. |
| `AL230` | Semantic Duplicate Across Agents | Several targets say the same rule in different words. | Collapse the semantic copies behind one shared owner. |
| `AL240` | Skill Hardcodes Invocation Inputs | A skill hardcodes changing subject, dataset, or case facts. | Keep the method in the skill and move changing facts into inputs or source reads. |
| `AL245` | Gate Declared As Inline Prose | Review gate IDs appear as free-form prose on the review or in an output field body instead of as typed `contract.NAME` identities. | Declare the gates once on the review contract and reference them by `contract.NAME` in the review body and the same identities through Doctrine interpolation in authored prose. |
| `AL246` | Per-Case Gate Delta Split Into Parallel Contracts | Two or more review cases share one `review_family` and differ only in a small gate delta, yet each case binds its own near-duplicate `contract:` workflow or schema. | Keep one shared contract and express the per-case delta through `override gates:` inside the case block. |
| `AL250` | Skill Capabilities Pulled Into Agent Role | The role prose tells the turn how to call a script, tool, or hard requirement that a skill should own. | Move the procedure into the skill; have the agent reference the skill. |
| `AL260` | Naked Script Or CLI Invocation In Role Prose | The role carries literal shell commands, exe paths, or flag lists as instructions. | Promote the invocation into a skill body and reference it. |
| `AL270` | Parallel Workflows As Review Contracts | Several `workflow` declarations share the same gate slot keys and each is bound as a review `contract:`. | Collapse into one `review_family` with shared gates and per-case prose. |
| `AL280` | Agent Skeleton Duplication | Several concrete agents restate the same declaration scaffold (`inputs`, `skills`, `outputs`, `output schema/shape`). | Hoist the shared scaffold into an `abstract agent` base. |
| `AL285` | Near-Duplicate Agents Differ Only By Typed Entity Reference | Two or more concrete agents share one abstract parent and differ only in one slot value that names a declared entity (document, schema, table, enum, agent, or workflow). The abstract marks that slot `abstract <slot_key>` with no type, so any family could bind and the constraint lives in prose. | Narrow the abstract slot to `abstract <slot_key>: TypedEntity`. Concrete children then bind by `name_ref` of that family, and `E538` / `E539` catch wrong-family or unresolved bindings at compile time. |
| `AL290` | Intra-Agent Rule Duplication | The same rule, prohibition, or step list is stated in this agent's `role:` body and also in the same agent's `how_to_take_a_turn`, `workflow:`, or `review:` surface. The two copies are not inherited from a shared declaration. | Pick one owner. If the rule is procedure, keep the workflow step and strip the role copy. If the rule is an enforced invariant, keep the review gate and strip the prose. |
| `AL300` | Runtime Boundary Leak | The prompt starts owning runtime state, safety control, memory, scheduling, or orchestration. | Remove runtime ownership from the prompt. |
| `AL310` | Shadow Control Plane | Prose creates a second source of truth that competes with a typed surface. | Delete the shadow surface and keep one canonical owner. |
| `AL320` | Host-Namespace Jargon Without Grounding | Prose uses harness-specific verbs, paths, or env vars without grounding. | Replace private jargon with neutral language or a shared grounded owner. |
| `AL330` | Typed Discipline Bash Escape | Prose carves out a Bash exception for a named verb set while neighboring skills go through a typed `$primitive`. | Wrap the allowed verbs in a skill scope and bind it. |
| `AL400` | Exact Truth Hidden In Prose | Exact requirements are hidden in prose instead of a typed surface. | Move exact requirements into the declared contract. |
| `AL410` | Prose Drift From Declared Constraints | Prompt text conflicts with exact supplied constraints. | Align the prose with the declared constraint surface. |
| `AL420` | Prose Names Artifact Not In Declared Outputs | Prose promises an artifact the declared output contract does not carry. | Add the artifact to the contract or delete the promise. |
| `AL430` | Deterministic Work Forced Into Prose | Prose is asked to do exact counting, validation, routing, or assignment work. | Move exact work into a typed surface or deterministic helper. |
| `AL440` | Declaration Name Quoted As String | A Doctrine declaration is named as a quoted literal where a typed ref would carry the truth. | Replace the string with the right typed ref. |
| `AL450` | Coarse Check Against Multi-Gate Contract | Review checks collapse a multi-gate contract to one rollup predicate. | Write one `accept` or `reject` per gate slot. |
| `AL500` | Mixed Role Ownership | One role owns too many jobs. | Narrow the role to one clear job and one clear output. |
| `AL510` | Missing Handoff Artifact | The role does not say what concrete artifact or blocker it must leave behind. | Require a concrete artifact or concrete blocker note. |
| `AL520` | Source Should Be Read, Not Remembered | The prompt tells the agent to work from memory when a real source should be read. | Point to the real source and remove memory-based fallback language. |
| `AL530` | Role-Shift In Process Without Stop Line | One process silently changes responsibility mid-sequence. | Add an explicit stop line and handoff artifact before ownership shifts. |
| `AL540` | Prose Routing Without Declared Next Owner | Prose tells the agent to route work without naming a declared next owner or route. | Use the declared route surface or name the exact next owner. |
| `AL550` | Read-Many Work Leaves Raw Notes | Read-many work leaves raw notes instead of one compact synthesized handoff. | Require one compact synthesis artifact. |
| `AL600` | Weak Resolver Name | A name is too vague to help a resolver or an author know what it is for. | Rename it so the job and scope are clear. |
| `AL610` | Weak Description | A description does not explain purpose, trigger, or boundary. | Rewrite the description with purpose, trigger, and limit. |
| `AL700` | Reading Level Too High | The prose is harder to read than the active style target allows. | Split long sentences and replace abstract words with common words. |
| `AL710` | Vague Wording | The prose uses vague verbs or nouns that hide the real action. | Replace vague verbs with exact actions and name the artifact directly. |
| `AL720` | Missing Priority Or Stop Line | The prompt gives several goals but does not say which comes first or when to stop. | Order the work and add a clear stop rule. |
| `AL730` | Quality Bar Mixes Gates With Craft | A quality bar mixes must-pass gates with taste advice. | Split hard gates from craft advice. |
| `AL740` | Machine-Language Prose | Role prose reads as state-transition code with long sentences, nested clauses, or inline `(a)`/`(b)` enumerations. | Split long sentences and rewrite at a 7th grade reading level in plain human speech. |
| `AL800` | Internal Contradiction | One surface gives incompatible instructions. | State the priority rule or split default behavior from exceptions. |
| `AL810` | Cross-Surface Contradiction | Two related surfaces disagree with each other. | Align local text with the shared source of truth. |
| `AL820` | Asymmetric When-To-Use Vs When-Not-To-Use | A skill or role defines overlapping or contradictory scope boundaries. | Rewrite the two scopes so they do not overlap. |
| `AL830` | Cross-Workflow Gate Id Drift | The same slot key appears in several workflows with divergent gate ids in prose. | Single-source the taxonomy through `review_family`. |
| `AL900` | Skill Too Broad | One skill mixes several unrelated jobs or reads like a handbook. | Split the skill by job and keep one repeatable method per skill. |
| `AL910` | Shared Law Trapped In Local Text | One local role carries a rule that should be shared by many roles. | Lift the shared law into a shared module or skill. |
| `AL920` | Compiler-Owned Semantics Restated In Prose | Prose restates verdicts, routing, or other semantics the compiler already owns. | Delete the prose copy and point at the declared surface. |
| `AL925` | Review-Gate Policy Restated In Prose | Role or workflow prose states a hard prohibition or invariant that a declared `review` gate on the same agent, or bound to the same work, already enforces mechanically. | Delete the prose restatement and trust the review. If the prose must mention the gate, cite it by `contract.NAME` instead of paraphrasing the predicate. |
| `AL930` | Skill Needs Host Contract | A bare `skill` imported across agents has prose naming host-owned slots. | Promote to `skill package` with `host_contract:` and `bind:` at each host. |
| `AL940` | Role Prose Shadows Typed Skill Scope | Role prose enumerates verb allow/blocklists that a typed skill scope already owns. | Drop the prose list; cite the skill by name. |
| `AL950` | Inlined Vocabulary Should Be An Enum-Typed Field | A fixed set of values is listed as prose (for example `A \\| B \\| C`) instead of a declared `enum` typed onto a field. | Declare `enum X: "..."` once, then write `type: X` on the field. |
| `AL960` | Process Evidence Emitted As Prose Not Typed Receipt | A skill's body or emitted artifact describes a run-by-run evidence envelope in prose rather than declaring a typed `receipt` host slot. | Promote the skill to a `skill package` and declare `receipt <slot>:` in `host_contract:` with typed fields; let critics bind the receipt by symbol. |
| `AL970` | Critic Re-Invokes Producer Skill Instead Of Binding Audit Mode | A critic uses a separate or duplicated skill to audit the producer's work instead of binding the shared skill with `mode audit = SkillMode.audit as SkillMode`. | Share one skill across producer and auditor and declare the critic's bind with `mode audit = ...`. |
| `AL980` | Output-Shape Selector Uses Deprecated Enum-Only Mode Form | A selector on an output shape still uses the old `mode role as WriterRole` enum-only form instead of the canonical `mode role = WriterRole.<case> as WriterRole` expr form. | Rewrite each selector to the expr-based form so the compiler can validate the picked case against the enum. |
| `AL990` | Project Lacks An Enforcement Rule For Shared Inheritance Invariant | A set of concrete agents in the same role class all share the same required ancestor, forbidden ancestor, or required slot through hand-authored discipline, but no declarative `rule` encodes that invariant. | Add one top-level `rule` declaration with a closed `scope:` predicate and a closed `assertions:` predicate so the compiler raises the matching `RULE###` code when a future author drops the shared surface. |
"""

    section full_calibration: "Full Calibration"
        section al100: "`AL100` Oversized Always-On Context"
            "What it means: The role home carries too much always-on text, or local prompt growth added bulk without buying clearer loading, stronger reuse, or stronger exact truth."
            "Why it matters: Context is a budget. Extra local text should earn something durable."
            "Default fix: Move deep reference material behind a pointer."
            "Good: `Read the quoting guide only when a quote is weak.`"
            "Bad: `Keep the full quoting guide, glossary, archive, and style handbook in mind on every turn.`"

        section al110: "`AL110` Pasted Reference Instead Of Pointer"
            "What it means: Long reference text is pasted where one pointer would do."
            "Why it matters: The same text will drift when copied, and copied reference text is a common way to add bulk without creating reuse."
            "Default fix: Replace the pasted block with one shared pointer."
            "Good: `Use the shared SummaryRubric skill before you finalize work.`"
            "Bad: `Here are the full 18 summary rules copied into this role home again.`"

        section al120: "`AL120` Deep Procedure In The Role Home"
            "What it means: A reusable method is taught inline instead of through a skill. A per-case decision taxonomy (if field X is populated, install rule Y; if entry Z appears, install rule W) is the canonical shape. A taxonomy that enumerates several decision branches with matching rule installs belongs in a skill body, not inline in the role."
            "Why it matters: The role home gets fat and the method cannot be reused cleanly. The added bulk did not buy reusable leverage."
            "Default fix: Move the method into a skill."
            "Good: `Use the InterviewSynthesis skill after you read the transcript.`"
            "Bad: `Step 1 read, step 2 cluster, step 3 compare, step 4 score, step 5 write...`"
            "Bad: `If the draft has a title, install a rename check. If the draft owns citations, install a source check. If the draft appears in an index, install an index-sync check...` — a per-case decision taxonomy with four or more branches inline on the role."

        section al130: "`AL130` Dead Inherited Section"
            "What it means: Inherited text is present but not used."
            "Why it matters: Dead inherited text hides the real active path."
            "Default fix: Drop the inherit or point to the step that needs it."
            "Good: `Inherit only the shared EvidenceCheck block that this role still calls.`"
            "Bad: `Inherit the full ReviewerWorkflow` with no remaining reference to it."

        section al140: "`AL140` Planning-Doc Scaffolding In Agent Body"
            "What it means: The emitted role body cites a planning doc by path, quotes a planning-doc rule ID, or carries authoring rationale that belongs in git history."
            "Why it matters: Authoring provenance burns always-on prompt budget and confuses the turn with content the runtime does not need. Rule IDs from planning docs drift the moment the plan ships."
            "Default severity: `high` on always-on role prose. Always-on bulk with no reuse is the worst class of bloat."
            "Default fix: Strip the citation and the rule IDs. Keep the behavior; drop the provenance."
            "Good: `Install each rule through the lens skill.`"
            "Bad: `Per rule L3-A1 in docs/CURRICULUM_L3_IMPLEMENTATION_2026-04-18.md, install each rule through the lens skill. The rationale for this rule is that the curriculum plan requires...`"
            "See also: `references/authoring-patterns.md` section `planning_doc_scaffolding`."

        section al150: "`AL150` Role Body Carries Markdown Section Tree"
            "What it means: The `role:` value is a multiline string that holds markdown headings (`##` / `###`), a numbered section list, or a similar section tree inside the string. The string's internal sections are invisible to the compiler: they cannot be inherited, overridden, shared with sibling agents, or targeted by `review`."
            "Why it matters: Doctrine renders one heading per typed slot on the agent, not per `##` inside a string. A section tree hidden in a role string burns always-on budget, loses composition, and drifts when a sibling agent tries to share the same structure. Every `##` inside the string is a slot the compiler could have been owning."
            "Default severity: `high` on always-on role prose when three or more internal sections are hidden inside one string. `medium` when one or two. Size alone is AL100's job; this finding fires on shape."
            "Default fix: Keep `role:` to a one-sentence headline. For each internal heading, introduce a typed agent slot (`your_job`, `workflow_core`, or a custom authored slot key) pointed at a `workflow` declaration with titled children. The rendered role then emits one heading per typed slot, each section becomes independently inheritable, and the compiler can see the structure."
            "Good: `role: \"Plan the revision pass.\"` plus `your_job: RevisionJob` and `standards: RevisionStandards`, where each slot names a workflow."
            "Bad: `role: \"\"\"## Identity\\nYou are the reviewer.\\n\\n## Scope\\nReview only the draft.\\n\\n## Output discipline\\nReturn one comment.\"\"\"` — three authored sections buried inside one string."
            "See also: `references/authoring-patterns.md` section `role_home_law` and the anti-pattern section `role_as_markdown_tree`; `examples/12_role_home_composition` for the typed-slot idiom applied to one or many agents."

        section al200: "`AL200` Duplicate Rule Across Agents"
            "What it means: The same rule or step list appears in several agents. A fixed vocabulary written as a pipe list (for example `A | B | C`) and repeated on several roles, or repeated once on a role and again as a critic gate check, is a canonical shape of this finding."
            "Why it matters: One rule should have one owner. When the repeat is a value vocabulary, the two copies drift and the critic gate can silently fall behind the producer prose."
            "Default fix: Lift the repeated rule into one shared skill or module. For a pipe-list vocabulary, declare an `enum` and type the field with it. The rendered schema now owns the vocabulary and the critic stops restating it. See also: `AL950`."
            "Shared owner: Almost always required."
            "Good: `Use the shared ClaimEvidenceCheck skill before you finalize work.`"
            "Bad: `Check each claim against a source quote. Mark weak quotes. Remove unsupported claims.` in three different roles."
            "Bad: `step_role values are introduce | practice | test | capstone` written once on the producer role and again as a critic gate."

        section al210: "`AL210` Repeated Method Should Become A Skill"
            "What it means: Several agents carry the same decision method with no skill owner."
            "Why it matters: A repeated method should have one reusable home."
            "Default fix: Extract the shared method into a skill."
            "Shared owner: Almost always required."
            "Good: `Use the FounderMatchMethod skill with the supplied founder set.`"
            "Bad: Three agents each teach the same clustering and compare method inline."

        section al220: "`AL220` Repeated Background Block Across Agents"
            "What it means: Several agent homes carry the same background or glossary block."
            "Why it matters: Shared background should not be copied into every role."
            "Default fix: Move the block into one importable module."
            "Shared owner: Almost always required."
            "Good: `Read the shared InterviewGlossary module when a term is unclear.`"
            "Bad: The same glossary paragraph is pasted into every interview role."

        section al230: "`AL230` Semantic Duplicate Across Agents"
            "What it means: Several targets say the same rule in different words."
            "Why it matters: Semantic copies still drift even when the wording changes."
            "Default fix: Collapse the copies behind one shared owner."
            "Shared owner: Almost always required."
            "Good: `Use the shared SafetyEscalation rule.`"
            "Bad: One role says `raise blockers early` while another says `surface risks before handoff` for the same policy."

        section al240: "`AL240` Skill Hardcodes Invocation Inputs"
            "What it means: A skill hardcodes the changing subject, dataset, or case."
            "Why it matters: The skill stops acting like a reusable method call."
            "Default fix: Keep the method in the skill and move changing facts into inputs or source reads."
            "Good: `Read the supplied founder application and the supplied source set.`"
            "Bad: `Read Maria Santos's application and Contrail's billing commits.`"

        section al245: "`AL245` Gate Declared As Inline Prose"
            "What it means: Review gate IDs appear as free-form prose on the review body or inside an output field body instead of as typed `contract.NAME` identities."
            "Why it matters: Typed gates are declared once on the `contract:` (either a `workflow` or a `schema`) and exported as `contract.NAME` symbols. Inline prose drifts from the contract, loses `E477` protection, and splits the gate taxonomy across surfaces."
            "Default severity: `high`. Gate drift breaks per-gate routing and failing-gate truth."
            "Default fix: Declare the gates once on the review contract. Reference them by symbol in the review body as `reject contract.NAME when ...` and `accept \"...\" when contract.passes`. Interpolate the same `contract.NAME` identities through the Doctrine interpolation root inside authored prose. A typo anywhere in the chain fails loud with `E477`."
            "Good: `reject contract.audience_named when DraftBrief.audience_missing` in the review body; the failing-gates prose then interpolates the same `contract.audience_named` and `contract.next_action_clear` identities so the taxonomy stays single-sourced."
            "Bad: A prose line on the review or output that says `List gates like 'audience_named' or 'next_action_clear' when they fail.` duplicating the contract."
            "See also: `examples/140_typed_gates_symbol_reference`, `examples/57_schema_review_contracts`, `examples/45_review_contract_gate_export_and_exact_failures`, and `AL450` when a multi-gate contract is collapsed into one rollup check."

        section al246: "`AL246` Per-Case Gate Delta Split Into Parallel Contracts"
            "What it means: Two or more review cases inside the same `review_family` differ only in a small gate delta, but each case binds its own near-duplicate `contract:` workflow or schema instead of sharing one contract with a per-case override."
            "Why it matters: Parallel contracts duplicate the gate taxonomy. One change has to land in every copy, and the per-case difference gets buried under boilerplate. The shared contract should stay the source of truth and only the delta should live on the case."
            "Default severity: `medium`. `high` when three or more cases each carry their own near-duplicate contract for what is really one gate family."
            "Default fix: Keep one shared `contract:` on the review or on each case and express the per-case delta with `override gates:` inside the case block. Use `add NAME: \"Title\"`, `remove NAME`, or `modify NAME: \"Title\"` so the contract owns the base taxonomy and each case owns only its own delta."
            "Shared owner: Almost always required."
            "Good: `Two cases in DraftReviewFamily share SharedReviewContract; the full-path case adds `override gates:` with `remove clarity`, `add depth: \"Depth\"`, `modify completeness: \"Completeness (full path)\"`.`"
            "Bad: `QuickPathReviewContract` and `FullPathReviewContract` declare almost the same gate slots, each bound to a different case in the same family."
            "See also: `examples/141_review_case_gate_override`, `references/reviews.md` section `per_case_gate_override`, and `AL270` when the duplicate contracts are also leaking into separate critic agents."

        section al250: "`AL250` Skill Capabilities Pulled Into Agent Role"
            "What it means: The role prose tells the turn how to call a specific script, tool, or CLI. A `skill` exists for the job (or should exist), but the procedure is being restated on the agent."
            "Why it matters: Agents should stay thin; skills should own capabilities. When a procedure lives on the role, one fix has to land in every agent that copied it, and the skill stops being the single source of truth."
            "Default severity: `high`. This is the primary thin-agent boundary violation."
            "Default fix: Move the procedure into the skill body. Have the agent cite the skill through a `skills:` block and reference it by declaration name."
            "Good: `Use the LensInstall skill to install each rule.`"
            "Bad: `Install each rule through authoring_lens/cli.py rules add via Bash. Verify the sha256 before proceeding.`"
            "See also: `references/authoring-patterns.md` section `skill_capabilities_in_role` and `references/skills-and-packages.md` section `where_tool_invocations_belong`."

        section al260: "`AL260` Naked Script Or CLI Invocation In Role Prose"
            "What it means: The role body carries a literal shell command, an executable path, or a flag list quoted as an instruction."
            "Why it matters: Even when no skill exists yet, command shapes belong on a skill, workflow, or document surface. Naked CLI in role prose fights the typed authoring model."
            "Default severity: `medium` on its own. Pair with `AL250` at `high` when a matching skill already exists."
            "Default fix: Promote the invocation into a skill body. If no skill exists yet, create one or point at an existing one."
            "Good: `Run the LensInstall skill.`"
            "Bad: `Run python authoring_lens/cli.py rules add --path ./rules --strict to install each rule.`"
            "See also: `references/authoring-patterns.md` section `naked_cli_in_role` and `references/skills-and-packages.md` section `where_tool_invocations_belong`."

        section al270: "`AL270` Parallel Workflows As Review Contracts"
            "What it means: Two or more `workflow` declarations carry the same gate slot keys and each one is bound as a review `contract:`."
            "Why it matters: The gate taxonomy now has several owners. One change has to land in every copy, and a critic binding can silently pick up the wrong contract."
            "Default severity: `medium`. `high` when the same abstract review base is instantiated in three or more concrete agents, each binding a different parallel contract."
            "Default fix: Collapse the parallel workflows into one `review_family` with a `selector` and exhaustive `cases:`. The taxonomy lives once; each case overrides only the per-mode prose."
            "Shared owner: Almost always required."
            "Good: `One review_family with selector: mode layer = ReviewFacts.layer as ReviewLayer and one case per layer.`"
            "Bad: Four `...ReviewContract` workflows with the same slot keys (`output_gates_pass`, `receipt_gates_pass`, `process_gates_pass`) each bound to a different critic."
            "See also: `references/authoring-patterns.md` section `parallel_workflows_as_review_contracts` and `references/reviews.md` section `review_families`."

        section al280: "`AL280` Agent Skeleton Duplication"
            "What it means: Two or more concrete agents restate the same `inputs`, `skills`, `outputs`, `output schema`, or `output shape` declarations when an abstract base could absorb them."
            "Why it matters: Each new child reruns the same scaffold. One change has to land in every file, and the real per-child difference gets buried under boilerplate."
            "Default severity: `medium`. `high` when more than three children share the same scaffold."
            "Default fix: Hoist the shared scaffold into an `abstract agent` base. Keep each concrete agent focused on the parts that truly differ."
            "Shared owner: Almost always required."
            "Good: `One abstract LensWardenBase carries the inputs, skills, outputs, and schema. Each concrete warden overrides only workflow, role, and the per-layer route.`"
            "Bad: Four warden files that each restate the same six imports, the same `inputs`, the same `skills`, the same `output schema`, and the same `outputs` struct."
            "See also: `references/authoring-patterns.md` section `agent_skeleton_duplication`."

        section al285: "`AL285` Near-Duplicate Agents Differ Only By Typed Entity Reference"
            "What it means: Two or more concrete agents share one abstract parent and differ only in a single slot value that names a declared entity (a document, schema, table, enum, agent, or workflow). The abstract parent marks that slot as `abstract <slot_key>` with no type annotation, so any family could bind there and the real type constraint survives only as prose."
            "Why it matters: The abstract slot should carry the real type. Without the annotation, a wrong-family binding (for example a workflow bound where a document was intended) compiles cleanly and the mistake only shows up at runtime. Untyped abstract slots also hide the pattern from the compiler, so refactors cannot rely on `E538` / `E539` to catch drift."
            "Default severity: `medium`. `high` when three or more concrete agents share the same slot and bind different declared entities."
            "Default fix: Narrow the abstract slot to `abstract <slot_key>: TypedEntity` where `TypedEntity` is the declared family (document, schema, table, enum, agent, or workflow). Each concrete child then binds `<slot_key>: <NameRef>` of that family. `E538` fires when a concrete binds to the wrong family or with an inline block. `E539` fires when the annotation names an unknown entity."
            "Shared owner: Almost always required."
            "Good: `abstract TypedPolicyReviewer carries `abstract policy: AccuracyPolicy`. AccuracyReviewer binds `policy: AccuracyPolicy` and ToneReviewer binds `policy: TonePolicy`. Both bindings are typed by the abstract.`"
            "Bad: `abstract PolicyReviewer carries `abstract policy` and a prose comment saying `must be a policy document`. Two concretes bind `policy: AccuracyPolicy` and `policy: SomeWorkflow` and nothing fails loud.`"
            "See also: `AL280` when the shared scaffold itself is the problem, and `examples/145_abstract_agent_typed_parameters/` for the canonical form."

        section al290: "`AL290` Intra-Agent Rule Duplication"
            "What it means: The same rule, prohibition, or step list is stated in this agent's `role:` body and also in the same agent's `how_to_take_a_turn`, `workflow:`, `review:`, or other authored slot. The two copies are not inherited from a shared declaration; they are two hand-written statements of the same rule in one agent file. This is the within-one-agent cousin of `AL200-AL230`; the fix differs because there is nothing to lift to a shared owner."
            "Why it matters: Two hand-written copies of one rule drift. The role copy pays always-on prompt budget for no new truth. Authors often duplicate because they do not trust one surface to carry the rule; the fix is to pick the surface that already loads when the rule is needed and delete the other copy."
            "Default severity: `high` when the duplicate is three or more sentences restated verbatim. `medium` when the two surfaces paraphrase the same rule without exact overlap."
            "Default fix: Pick one owner. If the rule is procedure, keep it in the workflow slot and strip the role copy. If the rule is an enforced invariant on a `review` gate, strip both the role copy and the workflow copy and trust the gate. If the role really is the right home, delete the workflow or review paraphrase."
            "Good: `role: \"Partition the draft across sections.\"` plus a `how_to_take_a_turn` sequence that carries the numbered steps once."
            "Bad: Role prose says `Do not cite deprecated sources.` and workflow step 3 also says `Skip any citation in the deprecated list.` — same rule, two hand-written owners, one file."
            "See also: `AL200` (cross-agent version with a different fix), `AL925` when the restated rule is enforced by a declared `review` gate, and `references/authoring-patterns.md` section `intra_agent_duplication`."

        section al300: "`AL300` Runtime Boundary Leak"
            "What it means: The prompt starts owning runtime state, safety control, memory, scheduling, or orchestration."
            "Why it matters: The prompt now competes with the harness."
            "Default fix: Remove runtime ownership from the prompt."
            "Good: `If a source is missing, leave a blocker note.`"
            "Bad: `Keep a safety strike count, auto-block future requests after three strikes, and rerun the cron in 30 minutes.`"

        section al310: "`AL310` Shadow Control Plane"
            "What it means: Prose creates a second source of truth beside a typed surface."
            "Why it matters: The agent gets two competing control planes."
            "Default fix: Delete the shadow surface and keep one canonical owner."
            "Good: `Follow the declared route surface.`"
            "Bad: `Ignore the declared route and send the work to ReviewerTwo if it feels right.`"

        section al320: "`AL320` Host-Namespace Jargon Without Grounding"
            "What it means: The prose uses harness-specific verbs, paths, or env vars with no grounding."
            "Why it matters: The role only makes sense inside one private host setup."
            "Default fix: Replace private jargon with neutral language or a grounded owner."
            "Good: `Use the available file-reading tools to inspect the source.`"
            "Bad: `Kick this through /tmp/agent_mux and write state to $BRAIN_SIDECHANNEL.`"

        section al330: "`AL330` Typed Discipline Bash Escape"
            "What it means: Prose carves out a 'permitted via Bash' exception for a named verb set while the rest of the file goes through `$primitive`-typed skills."
            "Why it matters: The carveout reintroduces the untyped tool surface the discipline was written to forbid. The compiler cannot verify the allowed verbs; one mutating call will not fail loud."
            "Default severity: `high`. The asymmetry with neighboring `$primitive` skills in the same file is the tell."
            "Default fix: Wrap the allowed verb set in a skill scope and bind it at every consuming agent. Drop the prose carveout."
            "Shared owner: Almost always required."
            "Good: `Use the $read-only-audit skill for the four read-only admin verbs.`"
            "Bad: `Critics are permitted to invoke the admin CLI via Bash: `rules list`, `receipts list`, `receipts read <id>`.`"
            "See also: `references/authoring-patterns.md` section `typed_discipline_bash_escape` and `references/skills-and-packages.md` section `where_tool_invocations_belong`."

        section al400: "`AL400` Exact Truth Hidden In Prose"
            "What it means: Exact requirements live in prose instead of a typed surface."
            "Why it matters: Exact truth in prose is hard to trust and hard to keep current."
            "Default fix: Move exact requirements into the declared contract."
            "Good: `The required fields live in the declared output contract.`"
            "Bad: `The output must have exactly seven keys and this exact nesting...` only in prose."

        section al410: "`AL410` Prose Drift From Declared Constraints"
            "What it means: Prompt text conflicts with exact supplied constraints."
            "Why it matters: The prose teaches behavior the exact surface does not allow."
            "Default fix: Align the prose with the declared constraint surface."
            "Good: `Use ReadFile and SearchDocs when you need source material.`"
            "Bad: `Use any browser or shell tool that seems useful.` when only two tools are allowed."

        section al420: "`AL420` Prose Names Artifact Not In Declared Outputs"
            "What it means: Prose promises an artifact the declared outputs do not carry."
            "Why it matters: The handoff promise is fake."
            "Default fix: Add the artifact to the contract or delete the promise."
            "Good: `Leave one compact founder brief.` and the output contract names that brief."
            "Bad: `Leave a risk register and a scorecard.` when neither output exists."

        section al430: "`AL430` Deterministic Work Forced Into Prose"
            "What it means: Prose is asked to do exact counting, routing, validation, or assignment work."
            "Why it matters: Deterministic work does not belong in latent judgment."
            "Default fix: Move exact work into a typed surface or deterministic helper."
            "Good: `Apply the seating rules from the typed seating surface.`"
            "Bad: `Seat 600 founders into tables of exactly 8 with no repeats and exact sector balance.`"

        section al440: "`AL440` Declaration Name Quoted As String Instead Of Typed Ref"
            "What it means: The role names another agent, output, review, schema field, or document as a quoted literal where a typed Doctrine ref would carry the same truth."
            "Why it matters: Quoted names decay. They do not move when the target renames. Typed refs (`inputs:`, `outputs:`, readable declaration refs, `from ... import ...`, addressable paths like `OutputSchema:field.subfield`) are the source of truth Doctrine already supports."
            "Default severity: `medium`. High on review- and route-carrying roles where the wrong name breaks routing silently."
            "Default fix: Replace the string with the right typed ref. See `references/imports-and-refs.md` for the full ref vocabulary."
            "Good: The role binds the next owner through a typed route field on `final_output.route:`, and the prose reads the route owner as a bare readable declaration ref."
            "Bad: `Hand the artifact to \"LessonPlanner\" via home:issue.md. Stamp the target_lesson_concepts_sha256 in the response.`"
            "See also: `references/authoring-patterns.md` section `declaration_as_string` and `references/imports-and-refs.md` section `prefer_typed_refs`."

        section al450: "`AL450` Coarse Check Against Multi-Gate Contract"
            "What it means: The bound review contract declares two or more named gate slots, but the review's `checks:` (or `contract_checks:`) block collapses every outcome to one rollup predicate such as `contract.passes`."
            "Why it matters: The typed gates are the whole point of the contract. A rollup hides which gate failed, and the compiler cannot route per-gate outcomes."
            "Default severity: `medium`. `high` when per-gate outcomes drive different next owners (for example, a setup-gate failure blocks the run while an output-gate failure routes back to the producer)."
            "Default fix: Write one `accept` or `reject` line per gate slot. Cite each gate by its exported identity (`contract.output_gates_pass`, `contract.setup_gates_pass`)."
            "Good: `accept \"Output gates pass.\" when contract.output_gates_pass` plus one `accept` per other gate."
            "Bad: `accept \"All gate groups pass.\" when contract.passes` when the contract declares five named gates."
            "Lint message: include the declared gate count so the author sees the missed granularity."
            "See also: `references/reviews.md` section `per_gate_checks`."

        section al500: "`AL500` Mixed Role Ownership"
            "What it means: One role owns too many jobs."
            "Why it matters: Mixed ownership makes stop lines and outputs fuzzy."
            "Default fix: Narrow the role to one clear job and one clear output."
            "Good: `Write the first summary draft.`"
            "Bad: `Read, score, rewrite, approve, publish, and notify the team.`"

        section al510: "`AL510` Missing Handoff Artifact"
            "What it means: The role does not say what concrete artifact or blocker it leaves behind."
            "Why it matters: The next owner cannot tell when the job is done."
            "Default fix: Require a concrete artifact or blocker note."
            "Good: `Leave one draft summary or one blocker note.`"
            "Bad: `Finish the work and hand it off.`"

        section al520: "`AL520` Source Should Be Read, Not Remembered"
            "What it means: The prompt tells the agent to work from memory when a real source should be read."
            "Why it matters: Memory is weaker than the source of truth."
            "Default fix: Point to the real source and remove the memory fallback."
            "Good: `Read the current pricing page before you summarize it.`"
            "Bad: `Use what you remember about our pricing model.`"

        section al530: "`AL530` Role-Shift In Process Without Stop Line"
            "What it means: One process silently changes responsibility mid-sequence."
            "Why it matters: Ownership shifts with no clean handoff."
            "Default fix: Add an explicit stop line and handoff artifact."
            "Good: `Stop after the draft. The reviewer owns final approval.`"
            "Bad: `Draft the summary, then approve it, then publish it if it looks good.`"

        section al540: "`AL540` Prose Routing Without Declared Next Owner"
            "What it means: Prose tells the agent to route work without naming a declared next owner or route."
            "Why it matters: The prompt invents routing outside the declared surface."
            "Default fix: Use the declared route surface or name the exact next owner."
            "Good: `Route to the declared Reviewer agent.`"
            "Bad: `Send this to whoever should handle it next.`"

        section al550: "`AL550` Read-Many Work Leaves Raw Notes"
            "What it means: Read-many work leaves raw notes instead of one compact handoff."
            "Why it matters: Raw notes slow the next reader and repeat work."
            "Default fix: Require one compact synthesis artifact."
            "Good: `Leave one founder brief with claim-vs-build gaps and timeline notes.`"
            "Bad: `Leave a folder of copied quotes and browser notes.`"

        section al600: "`AL600` Weak Resolver Name"
            "What it means: A name is too vague to help a resolver or author."
            "Why it matters: Weak names make the surface harder to load at the right time."
            "Default fix: Rename it so the job and scope are clear."
            "Good: `InterviewSummaryReviewer`"
            "Bad: `Helper`"

        section al610: "`AL610` Weak Description"
            "What it means: A description does not explain purpose, trigger, or boundary."
            "Why it matters: Resolvers and humans both get weak routing help."
            "Default fix: Rewrite the description with purpose, trigger, and limit."
            "Good: `Review one interview summary for evidence support and contradiction.`"
            "Bad: `Does review stuff.`"

        section al700: "`AL700` Reading Level Too High"
            "What it means: The prose is harder to read than the style target allows."
            "Why it matters: Dense wording slows tired readers and weakens execution."
            "Default fix: Split long sentences and use common words."
            "Good: `Read the transcript. Write one short summary.`"
            "Bad: `Synthesize the interview's multidimensional thematic landscape into a concise artifact.`"

        section al710: "`AL710` Vague Wording"
            "What it means: The prose uses vague verbs or nouns that hide the real action."
            "Why it matters: The agent does not know what concrete move to make."
            "Default fix: Replace vague words with exact actions and artifacts."
            "Good: `Leave one blocker note that names the missing quote.`"
            "Bad: `Handle any issues as needed.`"

        section al720: "`AL720` Missing Priority Or Stop Line"
            "What it means: The prompt gives several goals but does not say which comes first or when to stop."
            "Why it matters: The role can chase the wrong goal first."
            "Default fix: Order the work and add a clear stop rule."
            "Good: `Check evidence first. Then draft the summary. Stop after the draft.`"
            "Bad: `Check evidence, improve tone, fix structure, and keep going until it feels done.`"

        section al730: "`AL730` Quality Bar Mixes Gates With Craft"
            "What it means: A quality bar mixes must-pass gates with taste advice."
            "Why it matters: The reader cannot tell what is required versus preferred."
            "Default fix: Split hard gates from craft advice."
            "Good: `Must: every claim has support. Craft: keep the tone calm.`"
            "Bad: `The summary must be accurate, elegant, warm, and compelling.`"

        section al740: "`AL740` Machine-Language Prose"
            "What it means: Shipped role or skill prose reads as state-transition code instead of human instruction. Sentences longer than about 40 words, nested parentheticals, inline `(a)`/`(b)`/`(c)` enumerations, dense jargon, or code-like state-transition phrasing all qualify."
            "Why it matters: Doctrine treats a 7th grade reading level as a hard requirement for shipped bundled Markdown and agent replies. Machine-language prose burns budget and hides the real instruction. This rule strengthens `AL700`; `AL700` stays the broader reading-level rule, and `AL740` adds the machine-language triggers."
            "Default severity: `high` on agent role bodies. `medium` on skill body prose."
            "Default fix: Split every long sentence. Move enumerations into bullet lists. Replace nested clauses with two short sentences. Read the result out loud; if you cannot say it in one breath, split it again."
            "Good: `LensWarden installs each rule through the lens skill. Emit the review verdict once the install finishes.`"
            "Bad: `LensWarden, when invoked (typically after the section planner (which itself runs after the track planner)), must install each rule (a) by calling lens CLI rules add, (b) verifying the sha256, then (c) emitting the review verdict.`"
            "See also: `references/authoring-patterns.md` section `machine_language_prose` and `references/principles.md` section `p10`."

        section al800: "`AL800` Internal Contradiction"
            "What it means: One surface gives incompatible instructions."
            "Why it matters: The agent cannot satisfy both."
            "Default fix: State the priority rule or split default behavior from exceptions."
            "Good: `Be concise by default. Go longer only when the user asks for depth.`"
            "Bad: `Always keep the answer under five lines.` plus `Provide a full, exhaustive analysis.`"

        section al810: "`AL810` Cross-Surface Contradiction"
            "What it means: Two related surfaces disagree."
            "Why it matters: The author and shipped surface now teach different behavior."
            "Default fix: Align local text with the shared source of truth."
            "Good: Authored and emitted tool guidance both say `Use ReadFile and SearchDocs.`"
            "Bad: Authored text says `Use any browser or shell tool.` while the emitted skill says otherwise."

        section al820: "`AL820` Asymmetric When-To-Use Vs When-Not-To-Use"
            "What it means: A skill or role defines overlapping or contradictory scope boundaries."
            "Why it matters: The resolver cannot tell when the skill should load."
            "Default fix: Rewrite the two scopes so they do not overlap."
            "Good: `Use for auditing prompts. Not for rewriting prompts.`"
            "Bad: `Use for any prompt work.` and `Do not use for prompt edits or prompt reviews.`"

        section al830: "`AL830` Cross-Workflow Gate Id Drift"
            "What it means: The same slot key appears in two or more `workflow` declarations, and the prose bodies reference gate ids that differ by punctuation, namespacing, or wording."
            "Why it matters: The taxonomy now teaches slightly different things in each layer. The author cannot tell which id is canonical, and downstream checks will drift."
            "Default severity: `medium`."
            "Default fix: Single-source the taxonomy through a `review_family` with shared `fields:` and `cases:`. The gate ids live once; cases override only the per-mode prose."
            "Shared owner: Almost always required."
            "Good: Every layer's case cites the same `setup_gates_pass` identity from the shared family fields."
            "Bad: One layer's `setup_gates_pass` prose references `setup.lens_rules_match_scope`; another references `setup_gates_pass` verbatim; a third references `setup_gate.match`."
            "See also: `references/reviews.md` section `review_families`."

        section al900: "`AL900` Skill Too Broad"
            "What it means: One skill mixes several unrelated jobs or reads like a handbook."
            "Why it matters: Broad skills undertrigger, overtrigger, and teach too much at once."
            "Default fix: Split the skill by job."
            "Good: One skill audits prompt quality."
            "Bad: One skill audits prompts, rewrites prompts, ships packages, and runs releases."

        section al910: "`AL910` Shared Law Trapped In Local Text"
            "What it means: One local role carries a rule that should be shared by many roles."
            "Why it matters: Shared law in one local file will drift everywhere else, and one rule change will need several edits."
            "Default fix: Lift the shared law into a shared module or skill."
            "Shared owner: Almost always required."
            "Good: `Use the shared EvidenceSupportLaw module.`"
            "Bad: One local role is the only place that says `Every claim needs a quote.`"

        section al920: "`AL920` Compiler-Owned Semantics Restated In Prose"
            "What it means: Prose restates verdicts, routing, or other compiler-owned semantics."
            "Why it matters: The prose copy can drift from the real compiler owner."
            "Default fix: Delete the prose copy and point at the declared surface."
            "Good: `Follow the declared route surface.`"
            "Bad: `If branch A happens, route to Reviewer; if branch B happens, stop with no owner.` copied into prose beside the real route surface."

        section al925: "`AL925` Review-Gate Policy Restated In Prose"
            "What it means: Role or workflow prose states a hard prohibition or invariant that a declared `review` gate on the same agent, or a review bound to the same work, already enforces mechanically. The prose often paraphrases the gate's predicate in English. This is the review-gate cousin of `AL920`; `AL920` covers compiler-owned verdicts and routing, but author-declared review gates are not compiler-derived and slip past that finding."
            "Why it matters: The review is the fail-loud surface. Restating the gate in prose burns always-on prompt budget and signals that the author does not trust the review to carry the rule. The prose copy drifts the moment a gate is renamed or merged, and a new reader cannot tell which surface is authoritative."
            "Default severity: `high` when the prose explicitly names the same failure mode the gate catches. `medium` when the prose paraphrases the gate's intent without naming the failure mode."
            "Default fix: Delete the prose restatement. Trust the review. If the prose really needs to mention the gate for orientation, cite it by its `contract.NAME` identity through interpolation instead of paraphrasing the predicate. Pair with `AL245` when the gate itself is declared inline; the review contract should be the source of truth."
            "Good: `The review declares `gate sources_all_cited` on the contract. The role says nothing about it. Failing-gate prose interpolates `contract.sources_all_cited` when orientation is needed.`"
            "Bad: Role prose says `Never submit a draft without citations for every claim.` when the bound review contract already declares `gate sources_all_cited` that blocks exactly that. The prose is a second, drift-prone owner of the same rule."
            "See also: `AL920` when the restated surface is compiler-owned rather than a declared gate, `AL245` when the gate itself is declared inline, and `references/authoring-patterns.md` section `review_gate_restatement`."

        section al930: "`AL930` Skill Needs Host Contract"
            "What it means: A bare `skill` declaration is imported into two or more agents, and its `use_when:` (or `purpose:`) prose names host-owned slots or imperative write-targets like `cite into`, `emit into`, or `write to \"Scope And Receipts\"`."
            "Why it matters: The coupling between the skill's output and the host's document slots is carried in prose. The compiler cannot verify that a host actually provides the target slot, and one host that forgets the slot still emits a buildable agent."
            "Default severity: `medium`. `high` when the skill is imported into three or more agents."
            "Default fix: Promote the skill to a `skill package` with `host_contract:`. Let every consuming agent `bind:` the concrete slot once."
            "Shared owner: Almost always required."
            "Good: `skill package CatalogOpsSkill: host_contract: document handoff_section: \"Scope And Receipts\"` plus `bind: handoff_section: ScopeAndReceiptsSection` at each host."
            "Bad: A bare `skill` whose `use_when:` prose says `cite every receipt into \"## Scope And Receipts\"` and is imported into four agents."
            "See also: `references/authoring-patterns.md` section `skill_needs_host_contract` and `references/skills-and-packages.md` section `host_binding`."

        section al940: "`AL940` Role Prose Shadows Typed Skill Scope"
            "What it means: Role-body prose enumerates allowed or forbidden verbs with permission qualifiers (`may call`, `may not call`, `is permitted to`) when an imported skill package already types the verb set."
            "Why it matters: The allow/blocklist is advice the model either follows or does not. The real source of truth is the skill scope, and the prose copy will drift."
            "Default severity: `medium`. Pair with `AL250` when the prose also describes how to invoke the verbs."
            "Default fix: Drop the prose allowlist. The skill's scope is the source of truth; cite the skill by declaration name."
            "Good: `Use the $admin-lens skill for read-only admin work.`"
            "Bad: `The critic may call `rules list`, `receipts list`, `receipts read <id>`. The critic may not call `rules add`, `rules remove`, or any mutating verb.`"
            "See also: `references/authoring-patterns.md` section `machine_language_prose` and `AL250`."

        section al950: "`AL950` Inlined Vocabulary Should Be An Enum-Typed Field"
            "What it means: A fixed set of values is listed as prose instead of a declared `enum` typed onto a field. Common shapes are a pipe list (`A | B | C`) inside a role step, or a vocabulary repeated once on the producer role and again as a critic gate check."
            "Why it matters: The prose copy and the gate copy will drift. The rendered schema should own the vocabulary, not the role body."
            "Default fix: Declare `enum X: \"...\"` once with one member per value. Set the field's `type: X` on the schema, row_schema, item_schema, table column, or record scalar. Delete the prose and the duplicate gate line."
            "Good: `type: StepRole` on the `step_role` field, backed by `enum StepRole: \"Step Role\"` with members `introduce`, `practice`, `test`, `capstone`."
            "Bad: `step_role values are introduce | practice | test | capstone` written in the role body, plus `step_role_in_vocabulary` as a separate critic gate."
            "See also: `AL200` for the duplicate-rule framing, and `examples/139_enum_typed_field_bodies/` for the canonical form."

        section al960: "`AL960` Process Evidence Emitted As Prose Not Typed Receipt"
            "What it means: A skill's body, `use_when:` prose, or emitted artifact describes a run-by-run evidence envelope (confidence, sources, checks, receipts) in prose rather than declaring a typed `receipt` host slot on a `skill package`."
            "Why it matters: The prose envelope and any downstream critic gate will drift. A typed `receipt` host slot makes the envelope the contract and lets critics bind fields by symbol."
            "Default fix: Promote the skill to a `skill package` and declare `receipt <slot>:` inside `host_contract:` with one typed field per envelope part, backed by declared `enum`, `table`, `schema`, or `document` entries. Delete the prose copy."
            "Good: `receipt process_receipt:` with `confidence: ConfidenceLevel` and `evidence: list[EvidenceRow]` on the package; the critic references `producer.receipt.confidence` by symbol."
            "Bad: A skill body that says `always emit a short note about your confidence and a pipe-delimited list of the sources you checked.`"
            "See also: `AL930` for host-binding framing, and `examples/142_skill_host_receipt_envelope/` for the canonical form."

        section al970: "`AL970` Critic Re-Invokes Producer Skill Instead Of Binding Audit Mode"
            "What it means: A critic agent's `skills:` block declares its own copy of the producer's skill, or imports the same skill and lets the runtime guess intent, instead of binding the shared skill with `mode audit = <Enum>.audit as <Enum>` so producer and audit uses of the same capability stay compile-time distinguishable."
            "Why it matters: The producer and audit copies drift. The critic's role prose often restates the producer's prose to compensate. A mode-tagged binding keeps one skill, one package, and one contract while still letting the compiler reject audit-mode side effects (audit bindings cannot emit to `output` or `final_output` host slots; `E541` fails loud)."
            "Default fix: Declare one `enum SkillMode` with `producer` and `audit` members. Keep one `skill SharedSkill` declaration. On the producer agent, tag the binding `mode producer = SkillMode.producer as SkillMode`. On the critic agent, tag it `mode audit = SkillMode.audit as SkillMode` and leave any output-family host slots unbound."
            "Good: One `SharedSkill` declaration, a producer agent with `mode producer = SkillMode.producer as SkillMode`, and a critic agent with `mode audit = SkillMode.audit as SkillMode`."
            "Bad: Two near-duplicate skill declarations (`ProducerSharedSkill` and `CriticSharedSkill`) that point at the same package, or one skill used by both agents with no mode tag so the compiler cannot tell producer from audit."
            "See also: `AL900` for skill-scope framing, and `examples/144_skill_binding_producer_audit_mode/` for the canonical form."

        section al980: "`AL980` Output-Shape Selector Uses Deprecated Enum-Only Mode Form"
            "What it means: An `output shape` `selector:` block still uses the enum-only shorthand `mode <field> as <Enum>` instead of the canonical expr-based `mode <name> = expr as <Enum>` production shared with review cases, law matchers, and skill-binding modes."
            "Why it matters: The enum-only shorthand is soft-deprecated. The compiler now raises `E543` when it appears, and the form will be removed at the next minor language bump. Keeping one `mode_stmt` production across every dispatching surface also keeps authoring mental model small."
            "Default fix: Rewrite every `mode <field> as <Enum>` selector statement as `mode <name> = selectors.<field> as <Enum>` (or the corresponding expr for the selector source)."
            "Good: `mode role = selectors.role as WriterRole`"
            "Bad: `mode role as WriterRole`"
            "See also: `examples/138_output_shape_case_selector/` for the migrated canonical form and `examples/144_skill_binding_producer_audit_mode/prompts/invalid_enum_only_selector/` for the preserved `E543` regression fixture."

        section al990: "`AL990` Project Lacks An Enforcement Rule For Shared Inheritance Invariant"
            "What it means: A set of concrete agents in the same role class all share the same required ancestor, forbidden ancestor, or required slot through hand-authored discipline, but no declarative `rule` encodes that invariant. The next author can forget it, and nothing will fail loud at compile time."
            "Why it matters: The shipped `rule` primitive lets a project lint its own agent graph with closed `scope:` predicates and closed `assertions:` predicates. When the invariant exists only in reviewer prose or a human checklist, the compiler cannot raise `RULE003`, `RULE004`, or `RULE005` and the drift shows up later as broken runtime behavior or a bad review turn."
            "Default fix: Add one top-level `rule <RuleName>: \"<headline>\"` declaration. Pick a scope predicate from the closed set (`agent_tag:`, `flow:`, `role_class:`, `file_tree:`). Pick one assertion from the closed set (`requires inherit`, `forbids bind`, `requires declare`). Add a plain-English `message:` explaining the invariant. Verify the project still compiles and that removing the shared base now raises the matching `RULE###` code."
            "Good: `rule ComposersCheckUpstream: \"Every composer must inherit the invariant\"` with `scope: role_class: Composer` and `assertions: requires inherit UpstreamPoisoningInvariant`."
            "Bad: Every `*Composer` agent inherits `UpstreamPoisoningInvariant` by convention only, and a new `BriefComposer` that drops the inheritance compiles clean."
            "See also: `examples/146_declarative_project_lint_rule/` for the canonical form and one fixture per shipped `RULE###` code, and `docs/COMPILER_ERRORS.md` Rule-check codes section."

    section severity: "Severity"
        bullets levels:
            "`high`: likely to mislead the agent or create conflicting truth"
            "`medium`: likely to create drift, bloat, or poor reuse"
            "`low`: likely to reduce clarity, but lower risk"

    section confidence: "Confidence"
        bullets levels:
            "`high`: exact evidence and low ambiguity"
            "`medium`: strong evidence, but local intent might justify it"
            "`low`: weak signal and should stay hidden by default"

    section hybrid_checks: "Hybrid Checks"
        "These checks benefit most from exact side signals plus model judgment:"
        bullets codes:
            "`AL100`"
            "`AL130`"
            "`AL200`"
            "`AL220`"
            "`AL230`"
